-- FACTBOX: How Delta and potential merger partners compare
-- 
-- Thu Jan 10, 2008 3:08pm EST
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/01/10/us-airlines-idUSN1021676920080110

 

 NEW YORK  (Reuters) - A merger between Delta Air Lines Inc, the No. 3 U.S. carrier, and one of its main rivals would create the world's largest airline and likely kick-start long-expected consolidation in the U.S. industry. 

 Following is key data for Delta and its most probable merger partners, Northwest Airlines Corp and UAL Corp's United Airlines. The Wall Street Journal reported on Thursday that Delta plans to ask its board on Friday for permission to start merger talks with Northwest and United.  DELTA AIR LINES Headquarters Atlanta Hubs Atlanta, Cincinnati, New York, Salt Lake City Passenger traffic 122 billion RPMs (2007) (see notes) Revenue $19 billion Employees more than 47,000 Fleet 600 planes, including 133 CRJ-100/200 regional jets, 121 Boeing 757s and 120 MD-88s Major alliances SkyTeam, which includes Northwest and Continental Airlines; transatlantic joint venture with Air France-KLM  NORTHWEST AIRLINES Headquarters Eagan, Minnesota Hubs Detroit, Minneapolis/St. Paul, Memphis Passenger traffic 78 billion RPMs (2007) Revenue $12.4 billion Employees 29,579 Fleet 515 aircraft, including Boeing 747s and 757s, McDonnell-Douglas DC-9s and Airbus A330s, A320s, A319s Major alliances SkyTeam  UNITED AIRLINES Headquarters Chicago Hubs Chicago, Washington DC, Denver, Los Angeles, San Francisco Passenger traffic 117 billion RPMs (2007) Revenue $20 billion Employees 53,139 Fleet 460, including 97 Airbus A320s and 97 Boeing 757s and 94 737s Major alliances Star Alliance, which includes US Airways, Air Canada, and Germany's Lufthansa  NOTES Passenger traffic is measured in revenue passenger miles, or RPMs, the most common measurement of an airline's size, reflecting the distance traveled by paying passengers. Figures are for full year 2007. Revenue figures represent the average forecast by Wall Street analysts for 2007, according to Reuters Estimates. Sources: Companies, Reuters data (Reporting by  Bill Rigby ,  Chris Reiter , Kyle Peterson; Editing by  Brian Moss )